-- Copper Poised for Third Weekly Advance on U.S. Jobless Claims
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-08-16T03:35:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-16/copper-poised-for-third-weekly-advance-on-u-s-jobless-claims.html
Copper was set to gain for a third
week after an unexpected drop in U.S. jobless claims and
expanded manufacturing data signaled the world’s biggest economy
continues to mend.  Copper for delivery in three months on the London Metal
Exchange climbed as much as 1.4 percent to $7,410.25 a metric
ton, the highest since June 6, and was at $7,403.75 at 11:34 a.m.
in  Shanghai . Futures for delivery in December rose 1.2 percent
to $3.379 a pound on the Comex in  New York .  Claims for jobless benefits dropped last week to the lowest
level in almost six years, while manufacturing in the New York
region expanded in August for a third month. Copper prices will
be at or above current levels over the next decade, JPMorgan
Securities Plc analyst Fraser Jamieson said in a report
yesterday, citing stable through-the cycle demand, challenging
supply-side dynamics and rising capital expenditures and
operating expense.  “U.S. indicators yesterday helped improve  market
sentiment ,” said Xu Liping, an analyst at HNA Topwin Futures Co.
The economy in China, the world’s largest user, has gradually
been showing signs of a stabilizing, he said.  The contract for delivery in December increased 1.3 percent
to 52,740  yuan  ($8,629) a ton the Shanghai Futures Exchange.  On the LME, aluminum, zinc, nickel, lead and tin also rose.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
